******
[2]
Date: Tue, 12 Oct 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Cape Times via Independent Online, 12 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=vn20041012021628661C640112>

Dyer Island avian cholera under control
---------------------------------------
The outbreak of avian cholera on Dyer Island, which has killed 8000
Cape cormorants in the past week, is under control as fewer dead and
infected birds are being found. That's the word from Deon van
Geldenhuys of CapeNature, the conservation authority that manages
Dyer Island.
At the moment 10 CapeNature staff are patrolling the island 3 times a
day in search of sick and dead Cape cormorants, the prime victims of
the fatal bacterial disease.
"We are working many hours a day removing dead and sick birds from
the colonies," said Van Geldenhuys. "Sick birds that are alive are
being killed on the spot and burnt with the carcasses of the dead
birds. Unfortunately this is the only way to contain this disease,
which is highly contagious and always fatal. The cholera bacteria
can survive for up to 3 months after a bird has died."
He said CapeNature staff were well aware of how contagious the
disease was and were taking care not to fuel the outbreak. "We want
to make sure people are not carrying the disease to other parts of
the island or to the mainland. While working here, faeces might
stick to boots and clothes. Although it is not sure that faeces plays
a role in the spreading of avian cholera, everyone has to have
clothes and boots disinfected before leaving the island. To further
diminish the chance of spreading, masks and gloves are required, as
it is not clear if avian cholera is spread through inhaling," Van
Geldenhuys said.
Because of these strict precautions combined with the nature of the
disease, Van Geldenhuys is not worried about the cholera spreading to
the mainland.
"The disease tends to hit colonies of cormorants. As there are no
cormorant colonies on the mainland, we don't have to be afraid of
this disease spreading. Besides, we have not found any dead or sick
birds on the mainland so far," he said.
